observations.recommendation:
In order to establish accurately and reliably the balances of local road networks and the related existence and condition thereof, we recommend that the management undertake the following:
a. The Municipal Engineer and the Municipal General Services Officer/ Property Custodian conduct a yearly physical count of the local road network projects and consequently update the local road map of the LGU;
b. The General Service Officer/Property Custodian to prepare and maintain LRNLC and LRNPC as well as Local Road Inventory and Local Road Map;
c. The Municipal Accountant maintain Subsidiary Ledgers and RPI and conduct reconciliation with the GSO between the list of inventories per local road inventory report and road map with those recorded in the RPI.
d. The Municipal Accountant to take up the book value of Road Networks completed prior to CY 2016, if any; and
e. Municipal Accountant provide for the depreciation of road networks and the required disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-008.

In view of the above noted lapses, we recommended and Management agreed to require the following:
a. The Inventory Team conduct complete annual physical inventory-taking of PPE and reconcile the results with the Municipal Accounting Records;
b. The Municipal Accountant and the Property Custodian, in coordination with other department heads, exert joint efforts to create a complete set of property records, property cards and ledger cards for each type of PPE and henceforth, ensure that they are complete and regularly updated;
c. The Municipal Accountant drop in the PPE accounts the reported items totaling ₱172,225.67 listed in Annex F which do not qualify as PPE. Henceforth, ensure that all property and equipment recorded in the books qualify as PPE pursuant to Item 4.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006.
d. The Municipal Accountant update the lapsing schedule and ensure that all PPE have been provided with depreciation expense and that all data necessary have been appropriately logged in such as the acquisition cost and acquisition date;
e. The Municipal Accountant take extra care in the footing of figures to avoid errors in the recording of depreciation in the FS;
f. The Municipal Accountant compute the depreciation based on the five per cent of cost residual value pursuant to PAG 6 of IPSAS 17 and other applicable guidelines; and
g. The Municipal Accountant prepare an adjusting journal entry to correct the balances of the Accumulated Depreciation accounts to present fairly the PPE accounts.

In view of the above noted lapses, we recommended and Management agreed to the following:
a. Management submit the required detailed engineering documents, if any, henceforth, Management perform complete detailed engineering activities before the conduct of any bidding;
b. The BAC see to it that invitations are sent to various observers five days before the conduct of the eligibility checking, shortlisting, pre-bid conference, preliminary examination of bids, bid evaluation and post qualification. Said invitations should be properly filed and attached together with the contracts submitted so that the team will be able to determine management’s compliance with the said promulgation;
c. The BAC Chairman ensure that all the necessary information stated in Item 21.1 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184 are provided in the Invitation to Bid;
d. Management submit records of posting and downloading of the sale of bidding documents form the PhilGEPS website and the corresponding official receipts to serve as evidence that the approved bidding documents were readily available to interested bidders to serve as guide on the preparation of their respective bids;
e. Management submit the lacking documents listed in paragraph 11.20 and 11.32;
f. The BAC carefully examined the submitted technical, financial and legal requirements of the bidders to ensure that contracts are awarded to qualified bidders;
g. BAC see to it that after verifying the documents which would form part of the contract, the BAC properly affix their signature so as to ensure that no alterations will be made upon the submitted documents; and
h. Henceforth, the Management adhere to the transparency provisions as provided by the regulations cited above.

We reiterated our recommendations and Management agreed to:
a. instruct the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal General Services Officer/ Property Custodian to conduct yearly physical count of the local road network projects and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System and submit the same to the audit team;
b. instruct the Municipal Accountant to compute separately the depreciation for the road components based on their respective cost and useful life;
c. instruct the Municipal Accountant to provide required disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements in the format required by the COA Circular No. 2015-008;
d. instruct the General Service Officer (GSO) and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain LRNPC and LRNPC, respectively, and ensure that records are religiously reconciled; and
e. instruct the GSO to prepare and maintain The Local Road Inventory and Road Map and reconcile it with those recorded in the Registry of Public Infrastructure.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to intensify their efforts to establish the existence and validity and likewise collect said receivables, respectively;

b. direct the Municipal Accountant to conduct an assessment of the collectability of the dormant receivable accounts and request for write-off according to the procedures provided under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 and henceforth, prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for all receivables in accordance with Section 4(e) of the MNGAS for LGUs.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. ensure that all procurements be undertaken in accordance with the approved Annual Procurement Plan and that any changes thereto are included in the supplemental APP and submitted to the GPPB in July of the current budget year, and in January of the following budget year as provided under Sections 7.2 and 7.4 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
b. ensure that letters of invitation to attend the stages of the procurement process are sent to observers five days before the date of the procurement stage/activity and that duly received invitation letters be filed together with the contract documents submitted to the audit team in compliance with Sections 13.1 and 13.3 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
c. stop the practice of rescheduling the bid opening and/or any of the procurement stages/activities without just cause and without issuance of supplemental bid bulletin as required by the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184; and
d. ensure that contract documents are supported with complete supporting documents and observe strict implementation of the procurement process as provided under the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. instruct the Municipal Treasurer to remit to the GSIS the unremitted balance of ₱7,290.38 immediately and henceforth, ensure that withholdings of employees’ and employers’ contributions be remitted intact and within the prescribed period of the RA No. 8291;

b. instruct the Municipal Treasurer to submit copies of the Alpha-Lists to the audit team;

c. instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain schedules and/subsidiary ledgers to validate the balances of Due to GSIS account and submit the same to the audit team; and

d. instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that remittances of GSIS withholdings are supported with Disbursement Vouchers and proof of electronic payments to be attached with the Journal Entry Vouchers submitted to the audit team.

We have recommended the following:
 The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to install effective internal control on the municipality’s collection system including controls for the issuances, reporting, monitoring and safeguarding of all accountable forms of the municipality;
 The Municipal Treasurer to properly verify the Reports of Collections and Deposits of all collectors and monitor issuances and balances of accountable forms. Check the Statement of Accountable Forms as to initial balances on hand, receipts, issues and the ending balances on hand and make a physical count of accountable forms remaining in the custody of the collectors and check against ending balances on hand and make a physical count of accountable forms remaining in the custody of the collectors and check against ending balances on hand column;
 The Municipal Treasurer to issue new set of accountable forms to the collectors only when the previously issued accountable forms are fully issued and properly reported in the RCDs;
 The Municipal Treasurer to present all the unaccounted accountable forms and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor for verification and to come up with the audited Cash – Local Treasury balance.
 The Municipal Treasurer to submit Abstract of Collections in order to establish the amount that should be reported, particularly on the unreadable official receipts, both in the books of accounts and cashbooks.
 Valid justifications be submitted to explain the deficiencies noted on the unaccounted/missing accountable forms, and the delayed reporting of collections/late remittances.

We have recommended that:
 The management see to it that cash advances should be granted only to persons allowed by law to disburse and handle funds for the LGU;
 Payments for the payroll should be supported by complete documentation;
 The management thru the Municipal Accountant see to it that the prohibition of transferring cash advances between one AO to another should be strictly enforced; and
 The Municipal Accountant prepare the proposed adjusting journal entry in item 7.8.3.

We have recommended that the following actions be undertaken by management:
 Submit justification on the noted deficiencies;
 Implement only projects set forth in the budget. In instances where other priority projects are identified for implementation, a Sanggunian Bayan resolution should first be passed for the realignment and revision of the Annual Investment Plan to be submitted for approval by the SanggunianPanlalawigan;
 Revisit the DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2017-1 on the expenditure items not covered or are prohibited to be paid out of the 20% Development Fund for guidance;
 Justify the purchase of two (2) unit reconditioned mini dump trucks without authorization from the sanggunianand conduct of technical study. Moreover, submit the original documents covering the purchase of the dump trucks including the official receipts/ certificate of registration; and
 Henceforth, comply with the provisions of the IRR of R.A. 9184 with regards to Negotiated Procurement and other alternative of procurement.

We have recommended the following:
 Justify the noted lapses and henceforth, familiarize themselves with the relevant provisions with regard to the utilization of the LDRRM funds;
 Submit the essential documents enumerated under item 19.1.4 and 19.1.7 to support the validity of the pakyaw contract;
 Ensure the existence of appropriations before transactions are made or contracts are entered into;
 See to it that the amounts presented in the Notes to Financial Statements and Accomplishment Report tally; and
 Strictly utilize the LDRRMF for implementation of DRRM Programs and regular Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses are to be sourced from other funds.

In view of the foregoing, we have recommended that:
 The BAC members, BAC secretariat and TWG update and familiarize themselves with different rules and regulations on procurements as set forth by competent authority;
 Management use DPWH Department Order No. 72, series of 2016 or its updated issuances on the matter in its succeeding computation of the ABC of infrastructure projects for CY 2017 onwards.
